    <articletitle>
     Grade 1 or "ding" concussions in high school athletes.
    </articletitle>
    <pagination>
     <medlinepgn>
      47-54
     </medlinepgn>
    </pagination>
    <abstract>
     <abstracttext label="BACKGROUND" nlmcategory="BACKGROUND">
      Recent concussion management guidelines have suggested that athletes with mild (grade 1) concussions may be returned to play if asymptomatic for 15 minutes. The purpose of this study was to assess the utility of a current concussion management guideline in classifying and managing mild concussion.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="HYPOTHESIS" nlmcategory="OBJECTIVE">
      High school athletes diagnosed with a grade 1 concussion will demonstrate measurable decline in neuropsychological functioning that persists during the 1st week of recovery.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="STUDY DESIGN" nlmcategory="METHODS">
      Prospective study designed to evaluate neuropsychological functioning both prior to and following concussion.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="METHODS" nlmcategory="METHODS">
      Forty-three high school athletes completed neuropsychological test performance and symptom ratings prior to the season and at two times during the 1st week following mild concussion.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="RESULTS" nlmcategory="RESULTS">
      Thirty-six hours after injury, mildly concussed high school athletes demonstrated a decline in memory (P &lt; 0.003) and a dramatic increase in self-reported symptoms (P &lt; 0.00001) compared to baseline performance.
     </abstracttext>
     <abstracttext label="CONCLUSIONS" nlmcategory="CONCLUSIONS">
      Athletes with grade 1 concussion demonstrated memory deficits and symptoms that persisted beyond the context in which they were injured. These data suggest that current grade 1 return-to-play recommendations that allow for immediate return to play may be too liberal. Clinical Relevance: A reconsideration of current concussion grading systems appears to be warranted.
     </abstracttext>
    </abstract>
